MED4, also known as Mediator Complex Subunit 4, is one of the key subunits of the Mediator complex, a multi-subunit transcriptional regulatory complex. The Mediator complex regulates gene expression by interacting with RNA polymerase II (Pol II) and enhancer-bound transcription factors (Cevher et al.
2014
; Nath et al.
2020
). Mechanistically, MED4 stabilizes Mediator-Pol II engagement to potentiate transcriptional activation, notably enhancing APOE promoter activity. This regulatory function may exacerbate oligodendrocyte dysfunction through impaired lipid metabolism, ultimately contributing to myelin sheath degradation in pathological conditions (Blanchard et al.
2022
). The MED4-containing Mediator complex can form a molecular bridge with p65 (NF-κB), directly binding to the CSF3 promoter to regulate neutrophil activation and migration (Hwang et al.
2010
). This mechanism potentiates neuroinflammatory responses and exacerbates cognitive impairment in disease states (Garcia-Bonilla et al.
2015
).

