Neurexin 1 (NRXN1), a pivotal synaptic protein, plays a central role in synaptogenesis, synaptic maintenance, and the regulation of synaptic transmission (Shiota et al.
2022
). Extensive research has demonstrated that mutations in NRXN1 are implicated in various neuropsychiatric disorders, including autism spectrum disorder (Bourgeron
2007
), schizophrenia (Sebastian et al.
2023
), and dementia (Patel et al.
2023
). While NRXN1 expression demonstrates progressive downregulation during Alzheimer's disease (AD) progression (Gómez Ravetti et al.
2010
). It exhibits a unique compensatory upregulation in vascular dementia (VaD) pathogenesis. This dichotomy likely stems from distinct pathological mechanisms between these disorders: under chronic cerebral hypoperfusion, the glutamatergic synaptic networks with highest metabolic demands-particularly hippocampal CA1-dentate gyrus projections and orbitofrontal cortex-striatal connections-sustain primary ischemic damage (Alfaro-Ruiz et al.
2024
), thereby triggering NRXN1 upregulation. This adaptive response may confer neuroprotection through two mechanisms: first, by reducing oxidative stress in synaptic mitochondria and preventing degeneration of thalamocortical circuits (Bartoli et al.
2020
); second, by stabilizing presynaptic membranes to counteract neuronal damage caused by vascular hypoxia (Palermo et al.
2025
). This compensatory mechanism represents a unique neural adaptation to vascular injury that stands in marked contrast to the progressive synaptic protein depletion observed in AD. Protein-protein interaction analysis identified NRXN1 as exhibiting the highest connectivity with FN1 and H6PD. As a presynaptic membrane protein, NRXN1's extracellular domain binds to the extracellular matrix via fibronectin (FN1). FN1 serves dual roles as both a ligand for APOE-containing lipoprotein particles and a regulator of CSF3 receptor (CSF3R) membrane stability in microglia (Ito et al.
2014

