CSF3 also known as granulocyte-colony stimulating factor (G-CSF), is a cytokine that primarily functions by promoting the production and release of granulocytes from the bone marrow (Bor Tekdemir et al.
2020
). Recent studies have highlighted the significant impact of CSF3 on the pathological mechanisms and potential treatment of dementia. The reports indicate that in mouse models of AD, CSF3 enhances spatial learning abilities and significantly reduces amyloid deposition in the hippocampus and entorhinal cortex (Sanchez-Ramos et al.
2012
). Research suggests that CSF3 may improve non-spatial cognitive functions in patients with cerebral small vessel disease (CSVD) by restoring brain vascular endothelial cell function, repairing blood-brain barrier (BBB) damage, and reducing white matter lesions (Tuo et al.
2019
; Wei et al.
2017
). In this study, although the expression of CSF3 in the model group was higher than in the sham-operated group, the difference did not reach statistical significance. However, from a numerical perspective, this change still holds potential biological significance. This discrepancy may reflect the diverse roles of CSF3 in different pathological contexts. Studies have shown that cytokine levels in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) exhibit age-related changes in Alzheimer's disease patients, such as increased levels of TNF-α and IL-8 with advancing age (Hu et al.
2019
). Furthermore, the patterns of change in CSF Aβ42 and sTREM2 levels vary across different neurodegenerative diseases, suggesting that these biomarkers are associated with specific pathological mechanisms (Suárez-Calvet et al.
2016
; Spitzer et al.
2018
).
LRRTM4 exhibits highly selective expression in the brain, particularly at the excitatory postsynaptic sites of granule cells in the hippocampal dentate gyrus (Linhoff et al.
2009
). Loss of LRRTM4 function leads to reduced synaptic density, impaired AMPA receptor trafficking, and compromised synaptic function (Siddiqui et al.
2013
).
